Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{1/4%tsp} for the noodles.

Meanwhile, quarter the @closed cup mushrooms{150%g}. Halve the @bell pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Chop into 2cm pieces. Zest and halve the @lime{1/2}.

Once boiling, add the @egg noodle nests{2} to the water and bring back to the boil. Cook until tender, ~{4%minutes}. Drain in a #colander{} and set the pan aside.

> TIP: Run the noodles under cold water to stop them sticking together.

Pop the (now empty) saucepan back on medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{}.

When hot, add the mushrooms and pepper. Stir and cook until softened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Stir in the @Thai style spice mix{1} and @ginger, garlic & lemongrass puree{15%g}, then fry until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}.

> Add less Thai style spice blend if you'd prefer things milder.

Stir in the @coconut milk{200%ml}, @vegetable stock paste{10%g} and @water{300%ml} for the sauce.

Bring to a boil, then lower the heat and stir in the @peanut butter{30%g} until well combined. Simmer gently until the veg has softened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Meanwhile, crush the @salted peanuts{25%g} in the unopened sachet using a #rolling pin{}.

When the veg has softened, stir the cooked noodles into the laksa and heat through until piping hot, ~{1%minute}. Add a splash of water if it's a little too thick.

Stir in the @soy sauce{25%ml} and lime zest, then add lime juice and @salt{} to taste.

Share the laksa between your #bowls{} and finish with a sprinkle of peanuts over the top. Enjoy!